Based on the provided documentation, I found that deploying a workload on Google Cloud Pub/Sub involves creating a Pub/Sub function and configuring it to receive events from Pub/Sub. Here's a step-by-step guide:

1. Create a new Terraform configuration file (e.g., `main.tf`) with the required providers and resources:
```
terraform {
  required_providers {
    google = {
      source  = "hashicorp/google"
      version = ">= 4.34.0"
    }
  }
}

resource "random_id" "bucket_prefix" {
  byte_length = 8
}
resource "google_service_account" "default" {
  account_id   = "test-gcf-sa"
  display_name = "Test Service Account"
}
```
[Source: gcp/Cloud Functions/Terraform Pub/Sub TutorialStay organized with collectionsSave and categorize content based on your preferences. > Preparing the application]

2. Create a Cloud Function that consumes events from Pub/Sub:
```go
func helloPubSub(ctx context.Context, e event.Event) error {
  var msg MessagePublishedData
  if err := e.DataAs(&msg); err != nil {
    return fmt.Errorf("event.DataAs: %w", err)
  }
  name := string(msg.Message.Data)
  // Automatically decoded from base64.
  if name == "" {
    name = "World"
  }
  log.Printf("Hello, %s!", name)
  return nil
}
```
[Source: gcp/Cloud Functions/Locally test your function > Cloud Pub/Sub event-driven function example > Go]

3. Configure the Terraform configuration to deploy the Cloud Function:
```terraform
resource "google_cloudfunctions_function" "pubsub" {
  name        = "hello-pubsub"
  runtime     = "go113"
  handler     = "helloworld.helloPubSub"
  source_url  = "https://github.com/your-repo/your-function.git"
}
```
Note: Replace the `source_url` with your actual repository URL.

4. Initialize and apply the Terraform configuration to deploy the workload:
```bash
terraform init
terraform apply
```
