To secure an AWS VPC using IAM policies, you can use conditions in your policies to further restrict access. For example, you can specify that all requests must be sent using SSL or grant access to service actions if they are used through a specific AWS service.

According to the documentation [Source: aws/EC2/Example policies for working with the AWS CLI or an AWS SDK], you can use the `ec2:Vpc` condition key to specify that certain actions can only be performed on security groups in a specific VPC. For instance, the following policy grants users permission to add and remove inbound and outbound rules for any security group, but only if those security groups are in a specific VPC [Source: aws/EC2/Policy structure > Condition keys for Amazon EC2].

Here's an example of how you can use this condition key in your IAM policy:

```
{
  "Version": "2012-10-17",
  "Statement": [
    {
      "Sid": "",
      "Effect": "Allow",
      "Action": "ec2:AuthorizeSecurityGroupIngress",
      "Resource": "*",
      "Condition": {
        "StringLike": {
          "ec2:Vpc": "arn:aws:ec2:region:account-id:vpc/vpc-ec43eb89"
        }
      }
    },
    {
      "Sid": "",
      "Effect": "Allow",
      "Action": "ec2:AuthorizeSecurityGroupEgress",
      "Resource": "*",
      "Condition": {
        "StringLike": {
          "ec2:Vpc": "arn:aws:ec2:region:account-id:vpc/vpc-ec43eb89"
        }
      }
    }
  ]
}
```

This policy grants users permission to authorize inbound and outbound rules for any security group, but only if those security groups are in the specified VPC.

